ota of one post a month. So, just saying I&#8217;m alive. ;D</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="Leaves Texture" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/lokisky_walker/7308558200/" target="_blank"><img class="aligncenter" alt="Leaves Texture" src="http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7220/7308558200_a59a4f83dc.jpg" width="500" height="332" /></a></p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"http://localhost/skytreader.net/journal/alive-with-leaves/feed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:48:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:21:"For What Itâs Worth";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"http://localhost/skytreader.net/journal/for-what-its-worth";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:67:"http://localhost/skytreader.net/journal/for-what-its-worth#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 28 Apr 2012 08:31:14 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Reflections";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"i graduated";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"lists";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:37:"http://localhost/skytreader.net/?p=19";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:490:"After four years, I graduated, at last. I&#8217;m very happy that last Lantern Parade is indeed my last (as an undergraduate student of Computer Science, at least). And I&#8217;m more than happy to have graduated on time despite more than a few hitches in my trip. For two consecutive days I braved the heat of graduation ceremonies in aÂ barong tagalog. &#8230; <a href="http://localhost/skytreader.net/journal/for-what-its-worth">Continue Reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Chad Estioco";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3972:"<p>After four years, I graduated, at last. I&#8217;m very happy that last Lantern Parade is indeed my last (as an undergraduate student of Computer Science, at least). And I&#8217;m more than happy to have graduated on time despite more than a few hitches in my trip.</p>\n<p>For two consecutive days I braved the heat of graduation ceremonies in aÂ <i>barong tagalog</i>. It was, after all, for these ceremonies that I shared with my fellow (ex-?)students that I swallowed the unfair mismanagement of our undergraduate research project. But everyday I wake up after being judged to know, ummmm, &#8220;BS Computer Science&#8221;, I am always reminded that the ceremonies didn&#8217;t matter and were but mere formalities. It was the gradual steps we took towards graduation which (hopefully) made us deserving of what they conferred on us.</p>\n<p>I almost found myself crying after receiving my diploma that I found it difficult to smile for the photographs. Finally, after four years, I get to clean my room and my computer of all the accumulated &#8220;proofs of passing&#8221; I&#8217;ve been saving as a contingency plan, in case some disputes about my grades arise in the near future. Even right now, it is with great awe that I behold my passing grades in Discrete Math and Physics 72. Well, you never know.</p>\n<p>And because, thank thesis, it&#8217;s been over two months since I last posted here, I&#8217;m still too lazy to give anything coherent; I&#8217;m still catching up on missed sleep, missed games, and missed personal projects. So we eat up the rest of the space with my tips on how to make living on this rock we call the Earth a worthwhile endeavor.</p>\n<p><strong>Read books.</strong>Â Seriously. And I don&#8217;t just mean that you meticulously read ahead of this week&#8217;s lecture at school. I mean to say that you go out of your way and find books that will take you to worlds undiscovered and will bring you thoughts to ponder. The human civilization may be young compared to some alien culture lurking just behind the neighboring galaxies but we have already accumulated quite a trove of wisdom and almost all of them are recorded in books.</p>\n<p>Almost.</p>\n<p><strong>Have real-life adventures.</strong>Â Travel when and where you can. Take unknown paths. Do things without always knowing how they&#8217;ll turn out. This is how you&#8217;ll accumulate wisdom for yourself. You&#8217;ll surely be missing out a lot if you don&#8217;t read books but never ever forget that your life is one huge book-in-the-works as well and it will be such a shame to look back one day, realizing that your book is empty or well-written but unread. I am pleased to say that during my four years at college I&#8217;ve had my fair share of these adventures. Wish I took more field trips, though. I&#8217;m looking forward for more.</p>\n<p><strong>Make mistakes.</strong>Â Waste your time. You&#8217;ll thank yourself for it. If that book you are writing isn&#8217;t full of erasures you are most probably not trying out a lot of things. Don&#8217;t follow tried-and-tested recipes. That is not how you&#8217;ll learn.</p>\n<p><strong>Be aware of what you don&#8217;t know.</strong>Â And I assure you this will save your skin. And the skin of the people tossed with you in this adventure. Being aware of what you don&#8217;t know will help you make sense of your mistakes. You will be better prepared next time. Hallelujah to the things we don&#8217;t know.</p>\n<p>And lastly,</p>\n<p><strong>Do not listen to every advice thrown your way.</strong>Â I have come to accept that life, unlike research, does not require a theoretical framework for you to move forward. All you need is some nerve and, believe you me, you will be surprised how often this Universe/Fate/Destiny/Karma/God rewards raw nerve. Not always, but more often than what other people will have you believe. It is alright to just make things up as you go. No one will take it against you.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:63:"http://localhost/skytreader.net/journal/for-what-its-worth/feed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:54:"\n		\n